@flexiarg math-informal/complexity-classification
@title Complexity Classification
@sigils [⊞/階]
@keywords complexity, NP-complete, hardness, reduction, computability, classification
@audience theoretical-CS, combinatorics, logic
@tone analytic
@factor Discernment (paññā)
@family math-strategy/characterization-result
@references [math-informal/reduce-to-known-result math-informal/exhaustion-as-theorem math-informal/transport-across-isomorphism]

! conclusion:
  Place a decision problem (or a class of problems) in a specific complexity
  class — typically by exhibiting a reduction from a problem already in that
  class, or by proving membership constructively.

  + context: A computational problem P has been defined, and its complexity
    is unknown or only roughly known. The paper's contribution is to classify
    P at a known level of the complexity hierarchy: P, NP-complete, PSPACE,
    decidable, undecidable, ETH-hard, and so on.

  + IF:
      You can construct a polynomial-time (or appropriate) reduction from a
      complexity-class-complete problem to P, or vice versa, establishing
      membership / hardness with a sharp boundary.

  + HOWEVER:
      Complexity-classification is *one specific subtype* of
      `characterization-result` — its analogue in non-computational settings
      is `classification-result` (e.g., classifying KMS states or AFD outer
      actions). The reasoning shape is "list-the-cases-and-show-exhaustion"
      but the deliverable is "the problem belongs to class C" rather than
      "the structure has these instances." Use this leaf only when the result
      is genuinely complexity-theoretic.

  + THEN:
      1. Construct the reduction (typically polynomial-time many-one or
         Turing) from a complexity-class-complete problem to P (for
         hardness) or from P to a problem already in C (for membership).
      2. Verify the reduction is correct and within the resource bounds for
         the target class.
      3. State the classification theorem: P is C-complete (or C-hard, or
         in C, as appropriate).

  + BECAUSE:
      Complexity classification is structurally a *one-shot characterization*
      that places a problem at a precise location in a known hierarchy. It
      depends on the existence of a complete problem for the target class
      (Cook-Levin, etc.); reductions are the workhorse construction. The
      family parent is characterization-result; this leaf is the
      complexity-theoretic specialisation.

  + NEXT-STEPS:
      next[Identify the target complexity class and a complete / canonical problem in it.]
      next[Construct the reduction; verify resource bounds.]
      next[State the classification with the appropriate complete / hard / member language.]
